body:
@piiswrong It seems that you modified some shape related code of `SoftmaxOutput` in 2a9ca98e3ac12fb48848a4f88c29260f66f250b4 and a717570e3ea49f0761fef3779d88e0186f8dd6d5. It somehow broke our current speech demos (cc @antinucleon @yzhang87), and also I'm having a hard time to get the time-major layout RNN to work here. Could you give us a quick summary of what those modifications are suppose to do?

Specifically, it seems [this block](https://github.com/dmlc/mxnet/commit/2a9ca98e3ac12fb48848a4f88c29260f66f250b4#diff-772857f6d2e364650368f86ab6cdf11aL85) of modification is causing the issue. The original behavior of `SoftmaxOutput` is treating only the last dimension as the _class_ dimension. For example, if the input is of shape `(2, 3, 4)`, then the output is also `(2, 3, 4)`, while the label is of shape `(2, 3)`, as `4` here means 4 categories. This is also what the current `infer_shape` says.

However, if I understand correctly, it seems that modification is forcing the first dimension to be _number of samples_ and everything else is collapsed as categories. Is this intended behavior that is needed in some specific application? If it is, I guess we need to use a switch as we need the original behavior to properly support time-major RNNs.

As people are asking (#3142) how to use the new RNN symbol in mxnet, we provide this simple example as a demo. More importantly, this allow us to identify the use cases and issues we need to address. Currently we only have a wrapper to cuDNN RNN cell, so it is not available for CPU mode. Also we are working to stabilize the interfaces, as you can see from the comments of the demo, there are still many workarounds need to be applied to be able to work nicely with the rest of the mxnet high level APIs.

@sbodenstein @antinucleon One important issue I need to mention is that currently the LSTM cell takes all the parameters as a concatenated big vector. This is not compatible with our initializer architecture. 

I only verified it is able to run and the perplexity is decreasing. But I did not compare with our old LSTM implementation results.
